snippet.textDisplay:
It was worse than awful, I almost had a somewhat similar experience to yours. I watched the show all throughout HS and eagerly awaited the announced movie. I was a member of several Avatar The Last Airbender forums, talked about it in IRC chans and even discussed it on 4chan. My friends at school watched the show and loved it. Every new episode was discussed. It was great!
And then the first teaser was shown, people were very mixed, if I remember right, it just showed a Firenation ship throwing a giant fireball and as the camera panned back you saw a whole fleet of Firenation ships that also launched fireballs. Now that first teaser was alright, I was still 100% on board but there were many that were mixed on if it was going to be good.
At this point, I wanted to see it in theaters and resolved to watch it day 1 and with no spoilers (since I didn't know what was going to change)

Well, long story short, I did get to see it day 1 and it sucked so hard that I've never watched ANYTHING day 1 ever again. Lol. And I've only gotten burned many many times with adaptations afterwards. Of Intellectual Properties that I love.
Percy Jackson, Garfield, The Last Airbender ofc, The Wheel of Time, Netflix's DeathNote and more that I've blotted from my mind.
(Wheel of Time especially boiled my blood as I had Hopium once again and avoided leaks and spoilers and even re-read all the book in anticipation, fuck Amazon)

snippet.textDisplay:
"Avatar: The Last Airbender" holds an incredibly special place in my heart. It's not just a show I've watched; it's a journey I've embarked on multiple times, experiencing the magic of bending and the power of friendship in every episode. With each rewatch, I discover new layers of depth in the characters, their relationships, and the intricate world they inhabit. From Aang's journey of self-discovery to Zuko's redemption arc, I've laughed, cried, and cheered alongside them.

Sokka, with his wit and resourcefulness, never fails to bring a smile to my face. And that moment when Appa and Momo reunite with Aang? Pure joy. The show's ability to seamlessly blend humor, action, and heartfelt moments is a testament to its brilliance.

"Avatar: The Last Airbender" isn't just a series; it's a part of my own story, a source of inspiration that reminds me of the importance of balance, resilience, and the power of change. It's not just a show I've seen three times; it's an adventure I'm willing to embark on again and again.
